Fractal Control Principle: Sufficient Conditions for Emergence of Self-Similar Architectures under Latency, Uncertainty, and Resource Constraints


Author: Ouadi Maakoul

---

Abstract

This thesis develops a rigorous mathematical framework for the Fractal Control Principle (FCP) : under communication latency, partial observability, and bounded resources, complex multi-agent systems may evolve toward or be optimally designed as self-similar (fractal) hierarchical control architectures. We provide three theoretical contributions:

1. Existence of fractal fixed points (Theorem 1): Using a renormalization operator \mathcal{R} = \mathcal{C} \circ \mathcal{B} (coarse-graining followed by Bellman policy improvement) defined on a compact convex set of Lipschitz-bounded policies, we prove via Schauder’s fixed point theorem that there exists a scale-invariant policy \Pi^* = \mathcal{R}(\Pi^*). A Lipschitz-preservation lemma guarantees invariance of the policy space.
2. Stability and pathological fractality (Propositions 1–3): We prove a small-gain condition for two-scale and infinite hierarchies. For an exactly self-similar cascade with coupling gain k > 1/2, we show that the system becomes unstable despite each scale being input-to-state stable (ISS), formalizing the “fractal Rube Goldberg” failure mode. A fragility index quantifies the distance to this pathological regime.
3. Optimality conjecture: Under a bounded-rationality formulation, we conjecture that the optimal trade-off between latency, uncertainty, and resource costs yields a fractal dimension D_c \approx 1.5 for a range of parameters, derived from a first‑principles scaling argument.

All results are purely mathematical; no simulations or empirical validations are presented. The framework provides a foundation for designing scale‑invariant control architectures under constraints.

---

0. Related Work and Positioning

This thesis bridges several mature fields. We do not claim that fractal control is entirely new; rather, we provide the first unified framework that explains why and under what constraints fractal hierarchies emerge as attractors.

Hierarchical and multi-resolution control. Imura and Hara (2008) introduced Multi‑Resolved Dynamical Systems (MRDS) – a rigorous setting for aggregating agent states into clusters at different resolutions. Our definition of the control information dimension D_c is a direct adaptation of their complexity measure. However, MRDS assumes a fixed hierarchy; we show how the hierarchy can emerge via a renormalization operator.

Renormalization group in dynamical systems. Reynolds (2005) and others have applied RG to coarse-grain dynamical systems, showing that fixed points of the RG flow correspond to scale-invariant behavior. Our operator \mathcal{R} = \mathcal{C} \circ \mathcal{B} is a control-theoretic RG: coarse-graining followed by Bellman improvement. This is novel; prior work did not combine RG with optimal control or RL.

Fractal entropy and control. Gaudiano (2014) characterized fractal control systems via generalized entropy and multiscaling exponents. Our cost functional J and the optimality condition (Conjecture 1) extend his work by explicitly trading off latency and uncertainty.

Networked control with delay. Ballotta et al. (2021) proved that centralized architectures become suboptimal as inter-agent delay grows with the number of links. Our Lemma 2 (small-gain) is a direct corollary of their result. We go further by showing that the optimal topology often has a power-law cluster size distribution.

Input-to-state stability and small-gain. Mironchenko (2024) provides a comprehensive review of small-gain theorems for networks of ISS systems. Our Proposition 2 is a special case of his general result. The novel contribution is Proposition 3: exact self-similarity with gain k > 1/2 violates the small-gain condition and leads to the “fractal Rube Goldberg” instability. The extension to infinite cascades follows Dashkovskiy et al. (2010).

Bounded rationality. Gershman et al. (2015) introduced computational rationality as a framework for optimizing internal complexity. Our refinement of Conjecture 1 uses this lens: the fractal policy minimizes not only external costs but also the information‑theoretic complexity of the controller itself.

Positioning statement. No prior work formalizes a renormalization operator on the space of Lipschitz-bounded policies to prove existence of scale-invariant fixed points under explicit latency-uncertainty-resource trade-offs. The pathological instability (Proposition 3) is, to our knowledge, a new counterexample in small-gain theory. Thus, the FCP is a genuine synthesis and extension.

