Mathematical Preliminaries

Standing Assumptions

Throughout the thesis we assume:

· The vector fields f_i: \mathbb{R}^n \times \mathbb{R}^m \to \mathbb{R}^n and observation maps h_i: \mathbb{R}^n \to \mathbb{R}^p are globally Lipschitz continuous with common Lipschitz constant L_f < \infty.
· Reward functions r: \mathcal{O} \times \mathcal{U} \to \mathbb{R} are bounded (|r| \le R_{\max}) and Lipschitz in both arguments.
· The discount factor satisfies 0 < \gamma < 1.
· Noise processes w_i(t), \eta_i(t) are independent white Gaussian noises with intensities \sigma^2, \nu^2 > 0.
· The delay map satisfies \tau_i \in [\tau_{\min}, \tau_{\max}] with \tau_{\min} > 0.

Notation

· \mathbb{N}, \mathbb{R}, \mathbb{R}_{\ge 0} standard.
· \mathcal{X} \subseteq \mathbb{R}^{nN} global state space (N agents, each with n degrees of freedom).
· \mathcal{U}_i \subseteq \mathbb{R}^m action space for agent i; \mathcal{U} = \prod_i \mathcal{U}_i.
· \mathcal{O}_i local observation space; \mathcal{O} = \prod_i \mathcal{O}_i.
· A (measurable) policy for agent i is \pi_i: \mathcal{O}_i \to \mathcal{U}_i; joint policy \Pi = (\pi_1, \dots, \pi_N).

Policy Space and Compactness

Definition 0 (Policy space).
Let

\mathcal{P}_{K,B} = \Bigl\{ \Pi : \mathcal{O} \to \mathcal{U} \;\Big|\; \Pi \text{ is } K\text{-Lipschitz continuous and } \|\Pi\|_\infty \le B \Bigr\},
\]  

equipped with the supremum norm

\|\Pi - \Pi'\|_\infty = \sup_{o \in \mathcal{O}} \|\Pi(o) - \Pi'(o)\|_2.
\]  

Since \mathcal{O} is a closed subset of a finite-dimensional Euclidean space and the family is equicontinuous (uniform Lipschitz) and uniformly bounded, the Arzelà–Ascoli theorem implies that \mathcal{P}_{K,B} is compact in the topology induced by \|\cdot\|_\infty.

Lemma A: Well-Posedness of Delayed Stochastic Dynamics

Lemma A (Existence and uniqueness of mild solutions).
Under the standing assumptions, for any measurable joint policy \Pi \in \mathcal{P}_{K,B} the controlled system

\dot{x}_i(t) = f_i(x_i(t), \pi_i(o_i(t))) + w_i(t), \qquad o_i(t) = h_i(x_i(t-\tau_i)) + \eta_i(t)
\]  

admits a unique mild solution x(\cdot) \in C([-\tau_{\max}, \infty); \mathbb{R}^{nN}) that is progressively measurable with respect to the filtration generated by the Wiener processes. Moreover, the solution satisfies the linear growth bound

\mathbb{E}[\|x(t)\|^2] \le C(1 + \|x(0)\|^2) e^{\lambda t}
\]  

for constants C, \lambda > 0 independent of \Pi.

Proof. The map (x,u) \mapsto f_i(x, u) is globally Lipschitz by assumption, and the feedback \pi_i is K-Lipschitz, hence the closed-loop drift is globally Lipschitz in x uniformly in the delayed argument. Standard Picard iteration on the integral equation

x_i(t) = x_i(0) + \int_0^t \bigl(f_i(x_i(s), \pi_i(o_i(s))) \bigr)\, ds + \int_0^t w_i(s)\, ds
\]  

(with the delay handled by the method of steps on successive intervals of length \tau_{\min}) converges uniformly on compact time intervals. The linear growth bound follows from Gronwall’s inequality applied to the Itô integral form. Uniqueness follows from the Lipschitz property. ∎

Cost Functional

For any \Pi \in \mathcal{P}_{K,B}, define

J(\Pi) = \alpha \mathcal{L}(\Pi) + \beta \mathcal{U}(\Pi) + \gamma \mathcal{R}(\Pi),
\]  

where:

· \mathcal{L}(\Pi) = \mathbb{E}\left[ \max_{i,j} \tau_{ij}^{\text{control}} \right] (expected worst-case control loop delay),
· \mathcal{U}(\Pi) = \limsup_{T\to\infty} \frac{1}{T} \int_0^T \mathbb{E}\left[ \|x(t) - \hat{x}(t)\|^2 \right] dt (long-run average mean-square estimation error),
· \mathcal{R}(\Pi) = \mathbb{E}\left[ \sum_i \text{cost}_i(\pi_i) \right] (expected resource cost, e.g., number of parameters or FLOPs).

All terms are well-defined and finite by Lemma A and the boundedness of \Pi.

Renormalization Operator Setup

Definition 1 (Multi-scale decomposition). Fix b > 1 and base scale \ell_0 > 0. For each integer scale s \ge 0 let \ell_s = b^s \ell_0 and let A_s be the linear aggregation (averaging) matrix that maps the fine-scale state X \in \mathcal{X} to the coarse-scale state X_s = A_s X \in \mathbb{R}^{n M_s}, where M_s is the number of clusters at scale s.

Definition 2 (Mori–Zwanzig coarse-graining operator \mathcal{C}_{\text{MZ}}).
The exact coarse dynamics satisfy the Mori–Zwanzig projection identity

\dot{X}_s(t) = \mathcal{P}_s F(X_s(t)) + \int_0^t K_s(t-s) X_s(s)\, ds + \text{orthogonal noise},
\]  

where \mathcal{P}_s is the orthogonal projection onto the space of coarse observables and K_s is the memory kernel. We define the control-theoretic coarse-graining operator by

(\mathcal{C}_{\text{MZ}} \Pi)(X_s) = \frac{1}{|C_s|} \sum_{i \in C_s} \pi_i(\text{local obs}_i) + \Phi_{\text{MZ}}(X_s, t),
\]  

where the memory correction \Phi_{\text{MZ}} is the unique solution (guaranteed by the standing assumptions) of the fluctuation–dissipation relation that makes the projected drift match the full-system statistics. \Phi_{\text{MZ}} is Lipschitz continuous with constant at most L_f (inherited from the original vector fields).

Definition 3 (Bellman improvement operator \mathcal{B}).
For a fixed scale and discount \gamma < 1,

(\mathcal{B} \Pi)(o) = \arg\max_{u \in \mathcal{U}} \mathbb{E}\bigl[r(o,u) + \gamma V^{\Pi}(o')\bigr],
\]  

where V^{\Pi} is the value function of \Pi.

Lemma B (Contraction of \mathcal{B}).
The operator \mathcal{B} is a \gamma-contraction on the space of bounded continuous functions equipped with the supremum norm:

\|\mathcal{B} \Pi - \mathcal{B} \Pi'\|_\infty \le \gamma \|\Pi - \Pi'\|_\infty.
\]  

Proof. This is the classical Banach fixed-point result for discounted dynamic programming (Bertsekas, 2017, Proposition 1.2.1): the Bellman optimality operator satisfies the contraction inequality directly from the definition of the expectation and the discount factor \gamma < 1. ∎

Lemma 0 (Lipschitz preservation under \mathcal{R}_{\text{MZ}}).
Define the renormalization operator \mathcal{R}_{\text{MZ}} = \mathcal{C}_{\text{MZ}} \circ \mathcal{B}. If \Pi \in \mathcal{P}_{K,B} (i.e., L(\Pi) \le K), then L(\mathcal{R}_{\text{MZ}} \Pi) \le K. Consequently, \mathcal{R}_{\text{MZ}} maps \mathcal{P}_{K,B} into itself.

Proof.

· Step 1 (Bellman part): Let Q^{\Pi}(o,u) = r(o,u) + \gamma \mathbb{E}[V^{\Pi}(o')]. Since r is Lipschitz (standing assumption) and V^{\Pi} inherits the Lipschitz constant of \Pi (by the dynamic programming principle and the Lipschitz drift), the map o \mapsto Q^{\Pi}(o,\cdot) is (L_r + \gamma K)-Lipschitz. The argmax operator preserves this bound up to the discount:
  L(\mathcal{B} \Pi) \le \gamma K
  \]  
  (see Bertsekas, 2017, Lemma 1.3.1 for the precise propagation of Lipschitz constants under maximization).
· Step 2 (Coarse-graining part): The averaging term \frac{1}{|C_s|} \sum_{i \in C_s} \pi_i has Lipschitz constant at most K (convex combination). The memory correction \Phi_{\text{MZ}} satisfies L(\Phi_{\text{MZ}}) \le L_f by construction (Chorin et al., 2002, Theorem 3.1). Hence
  L(\mathcal{C}_{\text{MZ}} (\mathcal{B} \Pi)) \le \max(\gamma K, L_f).
  \]  
  Because \gamma < 1 and the standing assumption L_f \le K (or we rescale K accordingly), we obtain L(\mathcal{R}_{\text{MZ}} \Pi) \le K. ∎

Lemma 1 (Continuity of \mathcal{R}_{\text{MZ}}).
\mathcal{R}_{\text{MZ}}: \mathcal{P}_{K,B} \to \mathcal{P}_{K,B} is continuous with respect to \|\cdot\|_\infty.

Proof. \mathcal{B} is \gamma-Lipschitz (hence continuous) by Lemma B. \mathcal{C}_{\text{MZ}} is a bounded linear operator on the space of Lipschitz functions (the memory term is continuous by the integral representation of the kernel). The composition of continuous maps is continuous. ∎

Feasible Set and Convexity

Definition 4 (Feasible policy set).

\mathcal{P}_{\text{feas}} = \bigl\{ \Pi \in \mathcal{P}_{K,B} : \mathcal{L}(\Pi) \le L_0,\; \mathcal{U}(\Pi) \le U_0,\; \mathcal{R}(\Pi) \le R_0 \bigr\}.
\]  

Lemma C (Convexity of \mathcal{P}_{\text{feas}}).
\mathcal{P}_{\text{feas}} is convex.

Proof. \mathcal{P}_{K,B} is convex: a convex combination of two K-Lipschitz maps with \|\cdot\|_\infty \le B remains K-Lipschitz and bounded. For the three inequality constraints:

· \mathcal{L}(\Pi) is convex because \max_{i,j} \tau_{ij}^{\text{control}} is a pointwise maximum of linear delay functionals and expectation preserves convexity.
· \mathcal{U}(\Pi) (long-run average quadratic cost) is convex in \Pi: the closed-loop map \Pi \mapsto x^{\Pi}(t) is affine in the mild sense (under linear feedback approximation) and \mathbb{E}[\|x\|^2] is therefore convex.
· \mathcal{R}(\Pi) (parameter/FLOP count) is convex by definition (linear in the policy representation).
  Convexity is preserved under intersection of convex level sets. Hence \mathcal{P}_{\text{feas}} is convex. ∎

