Part I – Mathematical Framework: Fixed Points of Renormalization

1.1 Existence of Fractal Fixed Points

Theorem 1 (Existence of fractal fixed point).
Assume \mathcal{P}_{\text{feas}} is non‑empty. Then the renormalization operator \mathcal{R}_{\text{MZ}} = \mathcal{C}_{\text{MZ}} \circ \mathcal{B} has a fixed point \Pi^* \in \mathcal{P}_{\text{feas}}. This fixed point satisfies \mathcal{R}_{\text{MZ}}(\Pi^*) = \Pi^*, i.e., it is scale‑invariant (fractal) up to the discretization of scales.

Proof. By Lemma 0, \mathcal{R}_{\text{MZ}} maps \mathcal{P}_{\text{feas}} into itself (invariance). \mathcal{P}_{\text{feas}} is a closed subset of the compact set \mathcal{P}_{K,B} (by Lemma C and the definition), hence compact. \mathcal{R}_{\text{MZ}} is continuous (Lemma 1). Schauder’s fixed point theorem (a continuous map on a non‑empty compact convex subset of a Banach space has a fixed point) directly yields the existence of \Pi^*. ∎

Remark. Uniqueness is not guaranteed; we only claim existence. The fixed point corresponds to a policy that reproduces itself after coarse-graining and Bellman improvement – precisely a fractal control architecture.

1.2 Scale Invariance and Power Laws

Definition 5 (Fractal policy).
A policy \Pi is fractal (scale-invariant) if there exists a family of operators T_s (renormalization) such that for all scales s,

\Theta_{s+1} = T_s(\Theta_s),
\]  

and the control information dimension

D_c = \lim_{s\to\infty} \frac{I(U_s ; X_s)}{\log(1/\ell_s)}
\]  

exists and satisfies 0 < D_c < nN. Here I(U_s;X_s) is the mutual information between coarse actions and coarse states (Kraskov et al., 2004). This definition is representation-invariant.

Proposition 1 (Power‑law cluster distribution).
If a fixed point \Pi^* of \mathcal{R}_{\text{MZ}} is exactly scale‑invariant (i.e., \Theta_{s+1} = T_s(\Theta_s) for all s), then the cluster size distribution P(\ell) satisfies the scaling relation

P(b\ell) = b^{-\mu} P(\ell)
\]  

for some \mu > 0, implying a power law P(\ell) \propto \ell^{-\mu}.

Proof. Scale invariance implies that the probability of observing a cluster of size \ell is related to that of size b\ell by the same renormalization factor \lambda. Iterating gives P(b^k \ell) = \lambda^k P(\ell). For consistency with the normalization \sum_{\ell} P(\ell) = 1, we must have \lambda = b^{-\mu} for some \mu > 0. Hence P(\ell) \sim \ell^{-\mu}. ∎

The exponent \mu is not determined by the theory alone; it depends on the specific constraints and can be derived from the optimization in Part III.

