Part II – Stability Analysis and Pathological Fractality

2.1 Input‑to‑State Stability (ISS) for a Single Scale

Definition 6 (ISS, Sontag 1989).
The system \dot{x} = f(x,u) is input-to-state stable (ISS) if there exist \beta \in \mathcal{KL} and \gamma \in \mathcal{K} such that for all initial conditions x(0) and all bounded inputs u(t),

\|x(t)\| \le \beta(\|x(0)\|, t) + \gamma(\|u\|_\infty).

2.2 Small‑Gain for Two Scales

Consider two ISS subsystems coupled in a hierarchical (cascade) fashion:

\dot{x}_0 = f_0(x_0, u_0), \quad u_0 = k_0 x_1,

\dot{x}_1 = f_1(x_1, u_1), \quad u_1 = k_1 x_0,

where k_0, k_1 \ge 0 are coupling gains. Each subsystem alone is ISS with linear gain for simplicity.

Lemma 2 (Small‑gain condition for two scales).
If k_0 k_1 < 1, then the interconnected system is ISS. If k_0 k_1 > 1, the system can be unstable even though each subsystem is ISS.

Proof (constructive counterexample). Take linear systems: \dot{x}_0 = -x_0 + k_0 x_1, \dot{x}_1 = -x_1 + k_1 x_0. The state matrix is

A = \begin{pmatrix} -1 & k_0 \\ k_1 & -1 \end{pmatrix}.
\]  

Its eigenvalues are \lambda = -1 \pm \sqrt{k_0 k_1}. If k_0 k_1 > 1, then \lambda_+ > 0, so the system is exponentially unstable. Yet each isolated subsystem (\dot{x}_0 = -x_0 + u_0) is ISS with gain 1. ∎

2.3 Small‑Gain for Infinite Hierarchies (Dashkovskiy et al., 2010)

Consider a countably infinite cascade of scales s = 0,1,2,\dots with coupling gains k_s from scale s to s+1 (feedforward) and from s+1 to s (feedback). The interconnected system is described by:

\dot{x}_s = f_s(x_s, u_s), \quad u_s = k_s x_{s+1} \quad (\text{feedforward}), \quad u_{s+1} = k_{s+1} x_s \quad (\text{feedback}).

Theorem 2 (Small‑gain for infinite cascade).
Define the gain operator \Gamma on \ell^\infty by

(\Gamma y)_s = k_s y_{s+1} + k_{s+1} y_{s-1}.
\]  

If the spectral radius \rho(\Gamma) < 1, then the infinite cascade is ISS. In the case of exact self‑similarity k_s = k for all s, one finds \rho(\Gamma) = 2k (for symmetric coupling). Hence the condition for stability becomes k < 1/2.

Proof. This is a direct application of the small‑gain theorem for infinite networks (Dashkovskiy et al., 2010, Theorem 3.1). The spectral radius condition guarantees that the feedback loop has loop gain less than unity. For the self‑similar case, the tridiagonal Toeplitz matrix has eigenvalues \lambda_j = -1 + 2k \cos(\theta_j); the maximum real part is -1 + 2k, which is negative iff k < 1/2. ∎

2.4 Pathological Fractality: The Fractal Rube Goldberg Effect

Proposition 2 (Exact self‑similarity causes instability – nonlinear version).
For an exactly self‑similar hierarchy with coupling gain k > 1/2, the system can become unstable even if each scale is ISS. In particular, for k > 1, the spectral radius exceeds 1 and the instability is exponential.

Proof. The linearization around equilibrium yields an infinite tridiagonal Toeplitz matrix with eigenvalues \lambda_j = -1 + 2k \cos(\theta_j). The maximum eigenvalue is -1 + 2k. When k > 1/2, this eigenvalue is positive, indicating linear instability. For nonlinear systems, the Hartman–Grobman theorem (if the equilibrium is hyperbolic) guarantees that the linear instability persists locally. Hence the cascade is unstable. ∎

Definition 7 (Fragility index).
Let k_{\text{crit}} = 1/2 for the symmetric cascade. Define the fragility index

\mathcal{F} = \max\left(0, \frac{k}{k_{\text{crit}}} - 1\right) = \max(0, 2k - 1).
\]  

When \mathcal{F} > 0, the system lies in the pathological regime. In any well‑designed fractal hierarchy, we require \mathcal{F} \ll 1 (i.e., k significantly below 1/2).

Proposition 3 (Structural dissipation condition).
A necessary condition for stability of a fractal hierarchy is that the energy dissipation at scale s (measured by the Lyapunov decay rate \mu_s) exceeds the energy injected from scale s+1:

\mu_s > k_s \cdot k_{s+1}.
\]  

This is a scale‑wise small‑gain condition.

Proof. Apply the small‑gain theorem to each adjacent pair of scales. The condition \mu_s > k_s k_{s+1} ensures that the loop gain for the two‑scale subsystem is less than one. By induction, the entire cascade satisfies the spectral radius condition. ∎

Corollary (Fractal Rube Goldberg).
Exact self‑similarity with gain k > 1/2 violates the structural dissipation condition because then \mu_s = 1 (from the linear example) and k_s k_{s+1} = k^2 > 1/4. Consequently, the system becomes recursively overcomplicated and unstable – the “fractal Rube Goldberg” machine.

